The paper discusses the use of restricted Boltzmann machines (RBMs) for representation learning, which is a common topic in the machine learning community. The focus on parts-based discovery and the use of nonnegativity in the model weights suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning). The applications mentioned in the paper, such as handwritten digit recognition, face recognition, document classification, and patient readmission prognosis, suggest that the paper may also be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CL (Computation and Language), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
